<div id="review_1255152346" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1255152346" />
    <a title="Jeffrey (Akiva) Savett" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1289730-jeffrey-akiva-savett"><img alt="Jeffrey (Akiva) Savett" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1597028043p2/1289730.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1255152346?book_show_action=true">Apr 14, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeffrey (Akiva) Savett" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeffrey (Akiva) Savett" href="/user/show/1289730-jeffrey-akiva-savett">Jeffrey (Akiva) Savett</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780316288385" href="/book/show/3162674-independence-day">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1255152346" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4960360703048623905">I laughed out loud when I considered the box below this review where one can opt to hide his review lest he reveal any &quot;spoilers.&quot; That would be impossible for this novel. It is TRULY, to paraphrase Seinfeld, a book &quot;about nothing.&quot;<br/><br/>Well, wait. That&apos;s not totally true. There is that one thing that happens around page 300. I won&apos;t ruin it for you. Lord knows you&apos;ll have worked long and hard for it by then. It took me two MONTHS to finish this book. I stopped reading it several times and read, from</span>
  <span id="freeText4960360703048623905" style="display:none">I laughed out loud when I considered the box below this review where one can opt to hide his review lest he reveal any "spoilers." That would be impossible for this novel. It is TRULY, to paraphrase Seinfeld, a book "about nothing."<br /><br />Well, wait. That's not totally true. There is that one thing that happens around page 300. I won't ruin it for you. Lord knows you'll have worked long and hard for it by then. It took me two MONTHS to finish this book. I stopped reading it several times and read, from beginning to end, four other books.<br /><br />So why the four stars?<br /><br />Because Richard Ford is one hell of a writer. This book is basically a 450 page character sketch of Frank Bascombe. The frustrating thing is, Ford is MASTERFUL. I could probably read his grocery list and be entertained. Bascombe via Ford dispenses so many pearls of middle aged suburban wisdom that, at times, I wound up highlighting entire pages. There only a few authors I've read who could pull this off--this VERY light on plot, total reliance on character contract with the reader. Philip Roth is one. John Updike is another. Maybe John Irving, though, of course, with Irving you just know someone or something is going to get impaled. It's just a matter of time. So that's always exciting. In any case, I'll now add Ford to that impressive list of master craftsmen.<br /><br />But this style isn't for everyone. I loved the movie Boyhood. I heard some friends of mine criticize it, saying that "nothing really HAPPENS." That's what I liked about it in fact. That's what MOST of our childhoods are like. Things feel monumental in the moment; but by and large, the lucky majority of us get by with some stitches and broken hearts, some embarrassments and laughter. The same issues apply to this novel. Ford somehow does an amazingly entertaining job of capturing the banality and desperation of mid-life suburban self-creation. Of COURSE a few things "happen." But by and large, Frank Bascombe wants what we all want: for life to mean just a little something more than existence. But the beauty of Ford's character is that deep down he knows that even the self-imposed "existence period" following his divorce is an existential victory of value---maybe not a day of revolution, but an independence day nonetheless.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4960360703048623905" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


