<div id="review_576516107" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/576516107" />
    <a title="Tuckova" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/781918-tuckova"><img alt="Tuckova" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1348993712p2/781918.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/576516107?book_show_action=true">Mar 31, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tuckova" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tuckova" href="/user/show/781918-tuckova">Tuckova</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780747585244" href="/book/show/850057.Independence_Day">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/781918-tuckova?shelf=pulitzer">pulitzer</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer576516107" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4316182134231955740">Short version: SAD WHITE MIDDLE-AGED DUDE. HOW UNIQUE AND SPECIAL. <br/>Long version: I enjoyed the first part of this book. I liked the writing and the story he was telling about real estate and our complicated desires for home. Then he went to his girlfriend&apos;s house and it was pretty much downhill from there, because that is an inconsistent and unreliable narrator or a poor writer, and either way it wasn&apos;t fun anymore. The dialogues were so stilted and so awful that I couldn&apos;t relax into the book a</span>
  <span id="freeText4316182134231955740" style="display:none">Short version: SAD WHITE MIDDLE-AGED DUDE. HOW UNIQUE AND SPECIAL. <br />Long version: I enjoyed the first part of this book. I liked the writing and the story he was telling about real estate and our complicated desires for home. Then he went to his girlfriend's house and it was pretty much downhill from there, because that is an inconsistent and unreliable narrator or a poor writer, and either way it wasn't fun anymore. The dialogues were so stilted and so awful that I couldn't relax into the book any more, even when he was doing a perfectly nice job describing things -- anybody who talks with people the way Frank Bascombe talks to his girlfriend, his wife, his son, random dude at the hotel, whatever, is a person I don't trust. The relationship with the son in particular seemed off -- like we were supposed to understand why a loving father would reasonably cover up for what looked like a psychopath in the making (hiding the bird his son had killed and then going ON about the smell of the dead bird on his hands, like WASH THEM ALREADY), but I DIDN'T understand. It made me want to punch the father, not empathize with him. Mostly that was the feeling reading it, actually. I skimmed the end in case we came back around to the feeling of the promising beginning, but no. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4316182134231955740" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


